For me, this is my favourite kind of project! Something that makes an impact on a space in my home but also something I know I can change easily! The peel and stick market is one I have taken full advantage of and the quality of the products continue to improve! 

My Tips??
The preparation of the space where you are applying the product is super important! Make sure the surface is clean and free from dust and debris! Also dry fit your pieces and make a plan before applying the product. Even though it is peel and stick and you are supposed to be able to peel it of easily, this stuff is really sticky. You usually wouldn’t be able to reapply it after pulling it off completely.

That’s it, truly! 
I added three hinges to each half of our bifold. For the piece of the hinge attached to the doors, I used all 4 screws and the given screws that came with the hinges (these were 1/2 inch). When attaching to the door frame, I used screws I had a home that were longer, about 1 1/2 inch long to make sure they were secure. I also only used 2 holes that lined up with the wooden door frame and did not screw through the holes that lined up with the MDF trim. The knuckles of the hinge (the rounded part that allows the hinge to open and close) sat outside of the door frame and trim, so there was no need to notch it out. Because the doors fit snugly together, I did not need a magnetic latch for the top. If you decide to do this and your doors do not fit right together or swing open, you may want to add that to the supply list. 

Although some comments on my last reel suggested that the access to the closet would be more limited, this is not the case for me. It allows better access to the side of the closet where the bifold use to sit. 

Am I missing anything? Who is trying this next!? Stay tuned because the inside of the closet is getting an overhaul next!

Here are three things to consider when choosing paint colors for your home:

1. **Consider the Mood**: Think about the atmosphere you want to create in each room. Warm colors like reds and yellows can make a space feel cozy, while cool colors like blues and greens can create a calming effect. Neutrals like grays and whites provide versatility and can complement various styles.

2. **Test in Different Lighting**: Paint colors can look different under various lighting conditions. Always test your chosen colors in the actual space you plan to paint, considering both natural and artificial lighting, to ensure you like how they appear throughout the day.

3. **Create Cohesiveness**: Maintain a consistent color palette throughout your home to create a harmonious flow between rooms. Choose colors that complement each other and don’t clash. Using different shades of the same color or sticking to a particular color scheme can help achieve this cohesiveness.

Remember, personal preference matters too, so go with colors that resonate with you and make you feel comfortable in your space.

What side are you on??

I get asked a lot, why bother with the quick fixes (like this painted tile…that’s lasted almost 3 years by the way, with no touch ups😉).

So, hear me out…
I think when it comes to certain spaces in your home, a quick fix can sometimes be a better choice than tearing something out and replacing it with something brand new! Here’s a few reasons why…

First, environmentally it can be a much better choice. We live in a world where things are just not made to last anymore. If you live in an older home, chances are some of the materials may be better quality than what you would replace it with. Or if you have an old sofa or piece of furniture, it is likely a lot better than what you could buy now. Finding a way to update what we already have will also keep things out of the landfill which is always a plus!

Another reason is you can save a lot of money! DIY products like paint have come a long way. If you do your research and take the time to prep your space properly, your quick fix may just last the test of time!
You can also put your own creative touch on a design when you are not relying on what’s available in the stores.

Finally, I think trying out a quick fix first can help you really find out what you want for your forever choice. I painted my kitchen cabinets white about 4 years ago and although I love how bright they are, I find they show dirt around the bottom by our back door and I maybe would consider something else if we ever do a big renovation. 

So, if you don’t mind putting in some effort, sometimes the quick fix is the way to go!

If you’re diving into a home refresh after the holidays, styling open shelves in a living room can transform the space. Here are three tips to create a stylish display:

	1.	Balance and Grouping: Aim for a balanced look by mixing different heights, textures, and shapes. Group items in threes or odd numbers, such as a set of books vertically, a decorative vase, and a small potted plant. This creates visual interest and harmony.
	2.	Negative Space: Don’t overcrowd the shelves; leave some negative space to let the items breathe. It helps draw attention to individual pieces and prevents a cluttered appearance. Consider using larger decor pieces alternated with smaller ones to maintain a sense of balance.
	3.	Personal Touch: Infuse your personality into the display. Incorporate personal mementos, family photos in stylish frames, or souvenirs from travels. Mixing in personal items adds warmth and character to the shelves.

Remember, experimentation is key! Play around with the arrangement until it feels visually appealing and reflects your style. ALSO, don’t forget to shop your own home! Moving something from another room or searching in the back of your closet may allow you to freshen up the space without spending any money!!

Choosing the right rug is so tricky, especially when a lot of the rug shopping happens online now! I’ve tested and tried many styles in my home and I’ve learned a few things over the last few years!

1. For kids and pets stick with the low pile and easy to clean materials with synthetic fibers, like nylon or polyester. The rug I just added is 100% polyester and is easy to get pet hair out of and will clean well if there is a spill! You can also go washable if you want to be extra careful!

2. Layering helps to bring in more texture! You can add that easy to clean top layer over a natural fiber Jute or wool to bring in a little something more. If the spill happens on the bottom layer, hopefully you can rotate the rug and hide the stain under the couch😬

3. Use your rug to bring in some colour! I tend to stick with neutrals for my furniture and wall colour. Your rug is the perfect place to add a little bit of colour, even some earth tones if you don’t want to go too loud.
